{"title_page": "Ford Arena", "text_new": "{{Infobox stadium\n| stadium_name        = Ford Arena\n| nickname            =\n| image               = Ford Arena Beaumont Texas June 2014.jpg\n| image_size          = 235px\n| location            = 5115 [[Interstate 10 in Texas|Interstate 10]] South<br>[[Beaumont, Texas]] 77705\n| broke_ground        = 2001\n| built               =\n| opened              = November 8, 2003<ref name=\"SBJ\"/>\n| closed              =during the stupid covid-19\n| demolished          =(not yet)\n| owner               = [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson County]]\n| operator            = [[SMG (property management)|SMG]]\n| surface             = Multi-surface\n| construction_cost   = $32 million<br>(${{formatprice|{{Inflation|US|32000000|2003}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US}})\n| architect           = Long Architects Inc.\n| general_contractor  = Daniels Building & Construction Co.<ref name=\"SBJ\"/>\n| former_names        = Southeast Texas Entertainment Center<ref name=\"SBJ2\"/>\n| seating_capacity    = 9,737 (Concerts)<br>9,100 (Basketball)<br>8,200 (Ice Hockey)\n| tenants             = [[Texas Wildcatters]] ([[ECHL]]) (2003&ndash;2005, 2006&ndash;2008)<br>[[Beaumont Drillers]] ([[National Indoor Football League|NIFL]]/[[American Professional Football League|APFL]]) (2004&ndash;2008)<br>[[Southeast Texas Mavericks]] ([[American Basketball Association (2000&ndash;)|ABA]]) (2008&ndash;2011)<br>[[Oxford City FC of Texas]] ([[Major Arena Soccer League|MASL]]) (2012&ndash;2015)\n}}\n\nThe '''Ford Arena''' is a 9,737-seat multi-purpose [[arena]] in [[Beaumont, Texas]], [[United States|USA]]. The arena has 34,000 sq ft of exhibit space available for conventions and exhibitions.  It also includes 7 production offices, 3 dressing rooms, a 2,448 VIP Club, a 1,107 sq ft party patio, concession stands, and restrooms.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ford Park Entertainment Complex |url=http://www.beaumontcvb.com/listing/ford-park-entertainment-complex/396/ |publisher=Beaumont Convention and Visitors Bureau |accessdate=July  21, 2019}}</ref>  It is part of a larger suburban municipal complex called [[Ford Park]].<ref>http://www.fordparktx.com FordParkTX.com</ref>\n\n==Tenants==\n\n===Current===\n[[File:Ford Arena setup for arena soccer.jpg|thumb|right|Ford Arena set up for soccer in December 2014.]]\nFord Arena is the current Beaumont home of [[Disney on Ice]] and [[Stars on Ice]].\n\n===Former===\nFord Arena was most recently home to [[Oxford City FC of Texas]] (formerly the Texas Strikers) of the [[Major Arena Soccer League]].<ref name=\"ora120926\"/><ref name=\"beau140731\"/>  The arena was also home to the [[American Basketball Association (2000-)|ABA]] [[Southeast Texas Mavericks]] basketball team,<ref name=\"bmex110411\"/> [[NIFL]] [[Beaumont Drillers]] [[indoor American football|indoor football]] team, and the [[ECHL]] [[Texas Wildcatters]] [[ice hockey]] team.<ref name=\"kbmt121009\"/> In late 2005, the arena and park complex was used for [[Hurricane Rita]] relief, and no events were held there in the winter of 2005-06.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Ford Park]]\n*[[Montagne Center]]\n*[[Beaumont Civic Center]]\n*[[Fair Park Coliseum (Beaumont, Texas)|Fair Park Coliseum]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"SBJ\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Broughton |work=[[Sports Business Journal]] |title=Ford Park Means Arena, Ballfields and More |url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2003/11/20031124/Facilities/Ford-Park-Means-Arena-Ballfields-And-More-For-Beaumont-Texas.aspx |date=November 24, 2003 |accessdate=September 22, 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"SBJ2\">{{cite web |work=[[Sports Business Journal]] |title=What's on Deck |url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Journal/Issues/2001/07/20010730/Special-Report/Whats-On-Deck.aspx |date=July 30, 2001 |accessdate=September 22, 2011}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bmex110411\">{{cite news |first=Chad |last=Cooper |newspaper=[[The Examiner (Beaumont)|The 